Magicall Amage<br>
Master Summoner of the 62nd circle <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=xalmat@themagicianstower>Xalmat</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Master Summoner</span><br>  Posts: 568<br> <font color=#333333>(1/24/03 3:27:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8562.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Raid roles for Mages.</span><hr size=1> At the start of a raid, i begin by summoning pet gear. If pet classes want pet gear, they /tell me, and find me. No /tell, no gear. Next, I summon focus items, and make it plain and simple: Get your focus items now, or you don't get them. Once the raid actually starts I will not summon them.<br>
<br>
Before each major battle (specifically when we're rebuffing) I always mass mod rod. By the time you get your mana back, so will the buffers.<br>
<br>
Make sure they know what the focus items do:<br>
Necklace: Reagent Conservation<br>
Mantle: Buff Duration<br>
Earring: Mana preserve on <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Detrimental</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> spells (Heals and buffs are not affected).<br>
Ring: Cast time reduction (minimum cast time 3 seconds, Complete/Percentage Heal not affected)<br>
Bracelet: DD focus (Rains and AEs not affected)<br>
<br>
During the raid, I always summon single shot mod rods by /tell only. This lets me /rt<br>
<br>
As far as nuking and using a pet goes, use your best judgement. You're a damage dealing class, end of story. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hobiewankenobe>Hobiewankenobe</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://myweb.thump.net/1363/pictures/Gonn.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Master Summoner</span><br>  Posts: 549<br> <font color=#333333>(1/24/03 3:28:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8562.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://myweb.thump.net/1363/pictures/Gonn.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Raid roles for Mages.</span><hr size=1> These are my answers to your questions. My opinions and such, as other people will have other views.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>like the mana conservation item for a paladin or clerics do they really need these<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Make sure they know that the earring is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>not</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> aggro reduction. Some people still have that crazy idea (damn castersrealm).  Clerics and paladins sometimes nuke in addition to thier normal duties if they have excess mana. I know a cleric in my guild always asks for a focus bracer. My guess is though that they think the earring is aggro reduction.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>and clerics ask me for rods everytime they go out during the raid. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Rods are still fairly important. I get /telled for them often but with KEI (or better) and XPG, I don't usually lose much mana, so it's not a big deal when making them as I regenerate that mana back within a few seconds. Just do singles, only use the craped up mass group buff mod rods at the start.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Should i just save mana to nuke and make pets and things like that<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Make sure your guild is pet friendly. I have no clue what mobs your guild fights either, but some are very good to not have pets on. Make sureyou talk with your guild leader or whoever is in charge to find out when/where you can use them.<br>
<br>
Nuke when you can, but make rods and focus items. That's the one thing you can do for others that no one else can do, so it becomes the mages job.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=euphorion>Euphorion</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Conjurer</span><br>  Posts: 279<br> <font color=#333333>(1/24/03 3:29:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8562.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Raid roles for Mages.</span><hr size=1> Well, I'm usually the only mage at raids in my guild.<br>
Not too long ago we were in average not more than 15 people raiding and all the summoning was pretty ok.<br>
Lately we jumped to about 25 people on raids, among them many casters.<br>
And they had the habbit to ask for the items while we were already in raid area and about to engage the Mobs.<br>
First I tried it on the &quot;nice way&quot;: whenever somebody requested a focus item I asked them next time to ask before the raid.<br>
Didn't help.<br>
So with the support of the guildleader I made it clear that I will not summon any focus items during the raid unless I want to (meaning we have a bigger break anyway).<br>
After I replied for the first time &quot;no&quot; people learned it pretty well.<br>
<br>
As for Rods: usually everyone gets one when he asks for.<br>
I also asked the people to send me a tell right when they used the last charge so I have 5 minutes to summon it.<br>
Works pretty well.<br>
esp. when our clerics or our (usually only) enc of mainslower asks for one I will hold back nuking or whatever for that. <br>
because if they run oom and cant heal MT and he dies because of it that doesnt help me at all ;-)<br>
<br>
So I'm not going to summon every crap everyone remembers that he might need it whenever they ask for. Thy know what I can summon and can ask for it before the raid...if they don't...their fault.<br>
I don't care too much if a druid finds out that he has time to nuke and wants a bracelet while we are fighting some Mob. ;-) <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.euphorion.org/sig/euph_new2.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=woonx>woonx</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Arch Mage</span><br>  Posts: 307<br> <font color=#333333>(1/24/03 3:55:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8562.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Raid roles for Mages.</span><hr size=1> I would not say mages are a damage class, end of story. Mage are a damage class, with pretty nice utility spells. <br>
<br>
If you really care about your raid, you should be summoning all the focus items requested from you. Adding 10% to the nuking power of your dmg caster is worth it. Saving them up to 15% on mana useage too. Making your caster cast 15% faster matters too. I usualy don't get many request for neck and mantle...<br>
<br>
Equiping the pets in the raid is also important. You can mainly focus on the items that will help their offense (weapons, muzzle, belt/girdle) and leave out the defensive stuff (like armor) because pets on raid are there for damage, not tanking (unless you speakin about lower guk raid). Pet damage is something you have an impact on. If you can raise the raid dps by equiping pets, do it.<br>
<br>
Rods are your duty, it's much less of a pain now than it was pre-nerf (thank god), but it's still your duty. Usualy mass rod before the raid and then you are free for at least 15 minutes. Once raid is started, like mentioned in another post, have people send you tells for rods, then you can /rt and single rod them easily.<br>
<br>
Another important duty for a raiding mage is malosini(a) duty. This is one of the best debuff in game, you'll want it on most mobs you will be fighting. It will help damage, it will help other debuffs (slow, cripple, etc), it will basicly make life much easier for every casting class in your raid.<br>
<br>
Then there's firesheilds, we have the best sheilds in game, use them. Damage sheild over the course of a raid will do HUGE damage. Just know wich people in your raid will be tanking, and using a timer or a sheild on yourself or pet to time, keep them sheilded at all time.<br>
<br>
Lastly there is damage. Once all the other stuff is covered, then feel free to nuke your heart's content. <br>
<br>
The good side of this, is that you can do most of the utility side of your mage (rods, pet equip, firesheild) before the actual fight start, and once you do them, you have a nice interval where you will not need to cast them again, wich let's you med back and be ready for the fight. Mages are much more than simply nukers on raids, if you only play the nuke side, you'll end up being a weak wizzy with a pet, while you could be much more than that and be an awesome mage with a pet. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=75721">Woon</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->  <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://tde.e-slackers.net/">&lt;TDE&gt;</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> <br>
